  "Allegations" : "SEC LITIGATION RELEASE NO. 17461, DATED APRIL 5, 2002: THE SEC ANNOUNCED THE FILING OF AN EMERGENCY ACTION AGAINST DEFENDANT IN CONNECTION WITH A FRAUDULENT SCHEME THAT RAISED AT LEAST $52 MILLION FROM INVESTORS BETWEEN 1999 AND 2001. THE SEC ALLEGED THAT BRITISH CITIZEN AND OTHERS PROMISED INVESTORS EXORBITANT RETURNS (SUCH AS A NEARLY 300% RETURN IN TWELVE BANKING DAYS) THROUGH A HIGH YIELD TRADING PROGRAM PURPORTEDLY OPERATED BY AN INDIVIDUAL UNDER VARIOUS NAMES. ACCORDING TO THE COMPLAINT, THESE REPRESENTATIONS WERE FALSE BECAUSE SUCH HIGH YIELD TRADING PROGRAMS DO NOT EXIST, AND THE DEFENDANT AND OTHERS HAVE MISAPPROPRIATED OR OTHERWISE FAILED TO RETURN OVER $20 MILLION TO INVESTORS. THE COMPLAINT ALLEGES THAT, WITHIN THE PAST FEW MONTHS, THE DEFENDANT AND OTHERS HAVE EITHER CONTINUED TO ATTEMPT TO SOLICIT INVESTORS OR HAVE MADE MISREPRESENTATIONS TO INVESTORS REGARDING THEIR INVESTMENTS. THE COMPLAINT ALLEGES THAT DEFENDANT HERULA, THE REGISTERED REPRESENTATIVE FOR THE BUSINESS ACCOUNT, PLAYED INTEGRAL ROLES IN THE FRAUDULENT SCHEME AND ALSO MISAPPROPRIATED APPROXIMATELY $8 MILLION IN INVESTOR FUNDS. ACCORDING TO THE COMPLAINT, HERULA SOLICITED AN INVESTOR FOR TRADING PROGRAM IN 2001, AND HERULA HAS MADE FALSE STATEMENTS OR PROVIDED FORGED ACCOUNT STATEMENTS TO INVESTORS WITHIN THE PAST SEVERAL MONTHS. THE SEC ALLEGES THAT HERULA HAS RECENTLY TAKEN STEPS TO DISSIPATE ASSETS, INCLUDING PLACING HIS $5.5 MILLION HOUSE ON THE MARKET AND ATTEMPTING TO TRANSFER MONEY TO OFFSHORE ACCOUNTS. THE SEC ALLEGED THAT DEFENDANT HERULA VIOLATED SECTION 17(A) OF THE SECURITIES ACT OF 1933, SECTION 10(B) OF THE SECURITIES AND EXCHANGE ACT OF 1934 AND RULE 10B-5 THEREUNDER.",
